The secrets manager versus the parameter store.

Both services hold configuration and can encrypt it, but they split on rotation, cost, and integration. The secrets manager costs a small monthly fee per secret, has built-in automatic rotation, always encrypts, holds larger values, replicates across regions, and natively manages a database password's lifecycle. The parameter store is free at its standard tier, has no automatic rotation, encrypts only optionally for its secure type, holds smaller values, and doesn't replicate.

The rule is simple: if rotation is needed, use the secrets manager, for database credentials, expiring ay-pee-eye keys, and token secrets, anywhere automatic rotation is part of the security story. For plain configuration, feature flags, environment names, resource names, and non-secret values, use the parameter store, which is free at the standard tier and integrates with deployment everywhere.

Many architectures use both: secrets in the secrets manager, config in the parameter store.
